{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.29,0.19,0.07,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/735"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3809"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8143"},{"type":"tags","id":"8259"},{"type":"tags","id":"8286"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to a Breast and Endocrine surgical clinic. She initially presented with a 5 cm cancer in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast and a palpable left axillary lymph node. Biopsies confirmed a node positive, grade 3, triple negative infiltrating ductal carcinoma. She has now completed neoadjuvant chemotherapy and on examination, the breast and axilla appear normal. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her vital signs are within normal limits. A post-chemotherapy MRI shows no residual disease in the breast or axilla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surveillance","Left wide local excision and sentinel node biopsy","Left wide local excision and axillary node clearance","Left mastectomy and sentinel node biopsy","Left mastectomy and axillary node clearance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeoadjuvant chemotherapy results in a complete pathological response (cPR) in approximately 40% of patients, and up to 70% in those with triple negative or ER negative/HER2 positive disease. Surgery is still required to ascertain this important pathological information, even if there is complete clinical and radiological response. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the neoadjuvant chemotherapy has resulted in a complete clinical and radiological response, she can now be offered breast conserving surgery \u003Cstrong\u003Ewith wide local excision and sentinel node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. It is important that patients have the centre of their tumour localised (e.g. with a marking clip or carbon tract) prior to neoadjuvant chemotherapy to facilitate breast conserving surgery should the tumour disappear during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient had surgery first, she would have required a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft mastectomy and axillary node clearance\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is now accepted practice to perform a sentinel node biopsy after neoadjuvant chemotherapy, even in patients who initially had positive nodes on biopsy, provided that at least three nodes are sampled using the dual tracer technique of radioactive Tc99m and patent blue dye. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary node clearance\u003C/strong\u003E is not required if the sentinel nodes are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neoadjuvant chemotherapy can downstage breast cancer, allowing breast conserving surgery in some patients who would have initially required mastectomy.","Sentinel node biopsy can be performed after neoadjuvant chemotherapy, even in patients who initially had positive nodes, provided a dual tracer technique is used and at least three nodes are sampled.","Surgery is still required after neoadjuvant chemotherapy to determine pathological response, even if there is complete clinical and radiological response."],"references":["Ferrarazzo G, Nieri A, Firpo E, Rattaro A, Mignone A, Guasone F, et al. The Role of Sentinel Lymph Node Biopsy in Breast Cancer Patients Who Become Clinically Node-Negative Following Neo-Adjuvant Chemotherapy: A Literature Review. Current Oncology. 2023; 30(10):8703-8719.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37887530/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T13:49:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T13:49:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"735"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https